  +slide()
    p Students should learn programing in their native language...
    p ...in a fun and engaging environment.

  +step('0', '0', '4')#title
    span.try we introduce
    h1 transpyler<sup>*</sup>
    span.footnote <sup>*</sup><b>trans</b>lators for <b>Py</b>thon
    br
    span(style="font-size: 0.5em; position: relative; top: 0.2em; color: #666;").footnote.
      <sup>*</sup> we shamelessly stole this presentation from impress.js

  +step('850', '3000', '5', {rotate: 90})#try
    p.
      It is a framework for extending Python with <b>localized</b> keywords,
      standard lib functions, and types. <b>Transpyler</b> makes it easy to adapt Python
      to any language<sup>*</sup>.
    br
    p(style="font-size: 0.7em; text-align: right;").
      <sup>*</sup>It is already used by Pytuguês: Python to Portuguese extension

  +step('3500', '2100', '6', {rotate: 90})#big
    p it also integrates a
    b turtle
    p graphics implementation

  +step('2825', '2325', '1', {rotate: '0', z: -3000}).hide
    p
      img(src="pytuga.png", style='width: 800px')
    p(style="font-size: 0.5em").center.
      <sup>*</sup>it comes in any transpyler-based implemenation.

  +slide().hide
    h1 How does it work?
    ul(style="font-size: 0.8em")
      li It translates sources at the <b>token level</b>
      li Transpiles source back to Python
      li Functions use <b>gettext</b> for localization
      li The goal is to <b>extend</b> Python with translated keywords without replacing the original ones.

  +slide().hide
    :markdown-it()
      ```python
      from transpyler import Transpyler

      pytuñol = Transpyler(
          name="Pytuñol",
          translations={
              'def': 'función',
              'si': 'if', 'entonces': 'else',
              'regresar': 'return', ...
          }
      )

      # Now we can execute Pytuñol code
      pytuñol.exec(...)
      ```


  +slide().hide
    h1 Important features
    ul(style="font-size: 0.8em")
      li A <b>Jupyter</b> kernel
        ul
          li Python shell with bells and whistles
          li Remote code execution and <b>notebooks</b>
      li <b>QTurtle</b> application shown on the screenshot
      li It can use <a href="https://translate.google.com">translate.google.com</a> for help
      li Everything works around a single <b>Transpyler</b> subclass


  +slide().hide
      h1 Small history
      ul.small
        li <b>2015, Pytuguês:</b> supported only pt-BR.
        li <b>2017, Traspyler:</b> the recent effort to make that original implementation language agnostic.
        li Pytuguês is now only a thin layer around the Transpyler framework.
        li We created <b>Pytuñol</b>, es-BR, for this conference.


  +step('3500', '-850', '6', {rotate: -90, z: '0'})
    p(style="margin: 0 2em;").
      It is in an early development stage, but it has been used in the classroom
      to teach both <b>undergraduates and children.</b>


  +slide(0, -2000, '2', {z: -3000}).hide
      h1 Pedagogical results
      ul(style="font-size: 0.8em")
        li We only have data for <b>Pytuguês</b>
        li Used by ~200 students
          ul
            li It offers a natural migration path to Python
            li Students enjoy the <b>GUI</b> environment
            li Python has a shallow learning curve when compared to other languages such as C


  +slide(0, -2000).hide
      h1 Alternatives in Portuguese<sup>*</sup>
      ul(style="font-size: 0.8em")
        li
          b Scratch
          ul
            li Mature graphical environment
            li A natural starting point before Pytuguês

        li
          b Portugol
          ul
            li Multiple implemenations (usually PASCAL inspired)
            li Compiled and statically typed
            li Cannot use the ecosystem of the host language

      p(style="font-size: 0.5em; text-align: right") <sup>*</sup>we only consider localized computer languages


  +slide(0, -2000).hide
      h1 Why python?

      ul(style="font-size: 0.8em")
        li Dynamic interpreted language
          ul
            li The <b>REPL</b> is useful for exploration
            li Students focus on <b>algorithms</b> rather than on type declarations and on  compilation
        li Ecosystem
          ul
            li Jupyter <b>notebooks</b> are great teaching resources
            li Good libraries for common tasks:
            ul
              li games, graphics, web, numerics, etc
        li Widely used as a first programming language


  +step('7000', '-600', '6', {rotate: '0', z: '0'})
    p Colaboration is welcome!
    ul(style="font-size: 0.8em; margin-top: 0.5em;")
      li We want to support other idioms
      li Improve English and Portuguese <b>translations</b><sup>*</sup>
      li The <b>Qt</b> graphical interface is still unstable
      li + the usual chores:
        ul
          li documentation, testing, packaging, etc
    p.tiny <sup>*</sup>there is still some code left in Portuguese.


